386→                        <div id="content">Let $k\geq 4$ and $g_k(n)$ denote the largest $m$ such that there is a graph on $n$ vertices with chromatic number $k$ and girth $&#62;m$ (i.e. contains no cycle of length $\leq m$). Does\[\lim_{n\to \infty}\frac{g_k(n)}{\log n}\]exist?<br><br>Conversely, if $h^{(m)}(n)$ is the maximal chromatic number of a graph on $n$ vertices with girth $&#62;m$ then does\[\lim_{n\to \infty}\frac{\log h^{(m)}(n)}{\log n}\]exist, and what is its value?</div>
